As a Java/backend engineer, at one point these system design concepts become inescapable. Understand these concepts properly to be a better engineer and also to perform better during interviews:
Availability vs Reliability – Availability means the system is up and running; reliability means it works correctly over time without failure.
CAP Theorem – In a distributed system, you can only guarantee two out of three: consistency, availability, and partition tolerance.
CDN (Content Delivery Network) – A network of servers that delivers static content (like images or videos) from locations closer to the user.
Caching – Temporarily stores frequently used data to speed up future access.
Checksum – A small piece of data used to detect errors in files or messages.
Consistency Patterns – Strategies for making sure all users see the same data, either instantly or eventually.
Data Partitioning – Splits large datasets into smaller chunks (shards) to spread the load across servers.
Database Index – Like a table of contents for a database that helps find data faster.
Database Replication – Creates and maintains copies of data across different servers for better availability and fault tolerance.
Distributed Coordination Services – Tools (like ZooKeeper) that help manage and synchronize tasks across distributed systems.
Distributed File Systems – A system that lets you store and access files across many servers as if they were on one machine.
Distributed Messaging Systems – Enable services to communicate by sending messages asynchronously via a queue (e.g. Kafka, RabbitMQ).
Distributed System Design and Architectures
Domain Name System (DNS) – Translates human-friendly website names (like google.com) into IP addresses computers use.
Forward Proxy vs Reverse Proxy – A forward proxy hides the client from the server; a reverse proxy hides the server from the client.
Full-Text Search – Lets you search for words or phrases in documents or data like Google search does.
Heartbeat – A small, regular signal sent between components to check if they’re still alive and responsive.
Latency vs Throughput – Latency is the time it takes to process one request; throughput is how many requests are handled per second.
Load Balancer – Distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers to keep the system fast and reliable.
Long Polling vs WebSockets – Long polling repeatedly asks the server for updates; WebSockets keep a live connection for real-time communication.
Microservices – A system design where different features are split into small, independent services that work together.
NoSQL Database – A flexible, schema-less database designed for fast storage and retrieval of large amounts of data (e.g. MongoDB).
Notification System – Sends alerts or updates to users through email, push notifications, or SMS based on events.
Rate Limiting – Controls how many requests a user or client can make in a certain time to protect the system from abuse.
Scalability – The ability of a system to handle increasing traffic, data, or users without breaking or slowing down.
